Overview of data content

Columns Description
Year 2004-2008
Month 1-12 (January to December)
DayofMonth 1-31
DayofWeek 1-7 (Monday to Sunday)
DepTime Actual departure time (local, hhm m)
CRSDepTime Scheduled departure time (local, hhmm)
ArrTime Actual arrival time (local, hhmm)
CRSArrTime Scheduled arrival time (local, hhmm)
UniqueCarrier Unique carrier code
FlightNum Flight number
TailNum Plane tail number
ActualElapsedTime Actual Elapsed Time in minutes
CRSElapsedTime CRS Elapsed Time in minutes
AirTime Air Time in minutes
ArrDelay Arrival delay in minutes
DepDelay Departure delay in minutes
Origin Origin IATA airport code
Dest Destination IATA airport code
Distance Distance in miles
TaxiIn Taxi in time in minutes
TaxiOut Taxi out time in minutes
Cancelled Indicates if the flight was cancelled
CancellationCode Reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security)
Diverted 1 = yes, 0 = no
CarrierDelay Carrier Delay Time in minutes
WeatherDelay Weather Delay Time in minutes
NASDelay NAS Delay Time in minutes
SecurityDelay Security Delay Time in minutes
LateAircraftDelay Late Aircraft Delay in minutes

Before start, i decided to reduce the number of parameter to those i put in quote mark just above. I will make my analysis on potential factors wich impact the delay of flights and provide answer to these questions:

  • Are there certain destination or arrival cities that are home to more delays or cancellations?
  • What are the main factors behind the cancellation of flights?
  • What are the preferred times for flights to occur? Are there any changes over multiple years?

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are more than 24 Millions flights in the dataset with at least 20 features.

Most variables are numeric in nature as year, month, DayofMonth, DayOfWeek, ArrDelay, DepDelay,CarrierDelay, Cancelled, Diverted, WeatherDelay, NASDelay, SecurityDelay, LateAircraftDelay but the variables Origin, Dest, CancellationCode are categorical. Month: JAN - DEC
DayOfWeek: Monday - Sunday
CancellationCode: Carrier, Weather ,NAS ,Security

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best to predict if a flight will be delayed or cancelled. Also that could be interesing to find the preferred times for flights.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that flights are delayed and cancelled mainly due to Weather and Security.I also think that the preferred times for flights to occur are holidays (between july , august and september) whenenver the year. I have to explore variables linked to delay and flights cancellation.

In [16]:
def hist_delay(delay_parm, xlimx, xlimy,tick, tick_label, xlabel='', ylabel=''):
    """Plot the histogramm of delay based on standard scale"""
    binsize = 10
    bins = np.arange(df[delay_parm].min(), df[delay_parm].max()+binsize, binsize) 
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.hist(data = df, x = delay_parm,bins = bins)
    plt.xlim(xlimx,xlimy)
    plt.yticks(tick,tick_label)
    plt.xlabel(delay_parm)


def hist_log_delays(delay_parm,tick, tick_label, xlabel='', ylabel=''):
    """Plot the histogramm of delay based on log scale"""
    # there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
    log_binsize = 0.05
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(0.5, np.log10(df[delay_parm].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.hist(data = df, x = delay_parm, bins = bins)
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xticks(tick, tick_label)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.show()

delay_factors =['ArrDelay','DepDelay']
delay_factors_label = ['Arrival Delay (mn)','Departure Delay (mn)']
for i in range(len(delay_factors)):
    hist_delay(delay_factors[i],-50,400, [0,1e6,2e6,3e6,4e6,7e6],[0,'1M','2M','3M','4M','7M'],delay_factors_label[i])

The distribution is unimodal about the arrival delay time and slightly skewed at right. But that's normal because most of flight haven't delay at arrival.We can notice that the negative Arrival delay means that the airplane arrived early. Now let's take a look on the DepDelay.

I would restraints my analysis on flights started at time. In order to perform a log scale transformation.

But i was not completly sure that Carrier is the main cause of flights cancellation. Perhaps due to the high number of flights on some destinations cancelled due to Carrier. My new hypothesis is that during a specific month , there were a lot of flights cancelled due ether to Carrier or NAS.

That could be also interesting to discover the destinations that are home to more delays or cancellations. I looked at the data using a log transform because the delay minutes took a large range of values.

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.yticks([-20,0,10,20,30,40,50,60,120],[-20,0,10,20,30,40,50,60,120])
    plt.ylim(-50,100)

plt.figure(figsize = [16, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_dest_sorted, y_vars = numeric_delay_features, x_vars = categoric_cancellation_vars[1],

# compute the logarithm of price to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df_dest_sorted['Log_ArrDelay'] = df_dest_sorted[df_dest_sorted['ArrDelay']!= 0]['ArrDelay'].apply(log_trans)
df_org_sorted['Log_DepDelay'] = df_org_sorted[df_org_sorted['DepDelay']!= 0]['DepDelay'].apply(log_trans)

def scatter_delay(df, delay_param,factor_delay,xlabel,ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 6])
    plt.scatter(data = df, x = delay_param, y = factor_delay, alpha=1/10)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.xticks([10, 100, 200, 300, 500], [10, 100, 200, 300, 500])
    plt.yticks([10, 50, 100, 150, 200, 500], [10, 50, 100, 150, 200, 500])
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

def scatter_delay_log(df,delay_param,factor_delay,xlabel,ylabel):
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 6])
    plt.scatter(data = df, x = delay_param, y = factor_delay, alpha=1/10)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.yticks([10, 50, 100, 150, 200, 500], [10, 50, 100, 150, 200, 500])
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

# scatter plot of DepDelay vs. LateAircraftDelay, with log transform on DepDelay axis and ArrDelay vs NASDelay , with log transform on NASDelay
delay_params =['DepDelay','ArrDelay']
factor_delays =['LateAircraftDelay','NASDelay']
xlabels =['Departure Delay (mn)','Arrival Delay (mn)']
delay_params_log =['Log_DepDelay','Log_ArrDelay']
ylabels = ['Late Aircraft Delay (mn)','NAS Delay (mn)']
df_list =[df_org_sorted,df_dest_sorted]
for i in range(len(delay_params)):
    scatter_delay(df_list[i], delay_params[i],factor_delays[i],xlabels[i],ylabels[i])
    scatter_delay_log(df_list[i], delay_params_log[i],factor_delays[i],xlabels[i],ylabels[i])

The plot showed that even with a Late aircraft delay of 10 min , we can have a departure delay of more than 250 min and from 100 min of late aircraft delay, the delay at departure can quickly grow up to more than 500 min. So the impact of the late aircraft delay on the depature is important. The impact of NAS Delay on arrival delay is more important. Even with 10 min of NAS Delay , we can have more than 400 min of arrival delay.From 40 min of NAS Delay the arrival delay can quickly grow up to more than 500 min.

The NAS after some research proves to be important to guarantee the landing of an aircraft in better conditions.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I extended my investigation of destination or arrival cities that are home to more delays or cancellations. I discovered that delay factors are independant between them. But Carrier and NAS delays are highly correlated with the late at depature, followed by WeatherDelay. The Departure delay has also a high correlation with LateAirCraft delay. On another hand the Arrival delay has a high correlation with the NASDelay. I discovered also that some destination are always subjected to delays no matter when the departure from origin occured.(ORD and EWR). We can suppose that there is a lot of flights from or on these countries based on 2005 to 2008 data. During some specific months,some origin are most subjected to be delayed at departure. For example, in january at ORD.

About flights cancellation factors, carrier ,NAS and Wheather are more frequent. The majority of flights are could be cancelled due to weather especially in January, February and December just after carrier factor.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The more surprising, some destination are always subjected to delays no matter when the departure from origin occured. I'm sure that there are some others interesting features in this set of data. Perhaps with more data or adding data content on other year, i would find others interesting aspects.

Conclusions¶

In summary, i can say that through this dataset, there are some certain destnation or arrival cities that experience more delays. The main factors which could delay arrival or at worst cancel flights are the NAS and Carrier delay.
